Application 5

Author

Martin Hsu

Costco Time Markov Chains

Cars arrive at the Costco gas station at rate \(\lambda=1\) car per minute.

  • Cars arrive one-way to enter the gas station.
  • There are 3 islands with 2 pumps on each side, for a total of 12 pumps. Label the pumps in the back from left to right as 1, 2,\(...\), 6, and the pumps in front from left to right as 7, 8,\(...\), 12.
  • When cars arrive they join one of 6 queues, one queue for each side of the islands. There is one queue that waits for pumps 1 and 7, one that waits for pumps 2 and 8, and so on. The car first in line in the queue for pumps 1 and 7 will move to whichever one opens up first, similarly for 2 and 8, and so on.
  • There are 3 different types of cars: 30% of cars will only join the queues on the left (to wait for one of the odd numbered pumps), 30% of cars will only join the queues on the right (to wait for an even numbered pump), and the remaining cars will join any queue. (Idea: the pumps are supposed to reach to either side of a car, but this is harder to do for some cars (e.g.Â minivans), so some cars will only join the queues corresponding to which side their gas tank is on.)
  • When a car arrives, it will join whichever queue of its type is the shortest. If there is a tie for shortest queue of its type, the car will choose at random among the shortest queue options.
  • Once a car chooses a queue, it does not switch to another or leave the gas station before completing service.
  • Assume each pump serves customers at Exponential rate \(\mu=2\) cars per minute, independent of the customer type. You can assume that once a car completes service the next car in the queue starts service immediately. (Essentially, you can assume that any time between when one car finishes pumping and the next one starts has been accounted for in the service rate.)

Part 1

Let \(X_i(t)\) denote the number of customers in queue \(i=1,...,6\) at time \(t\), including any customers in service at the corresponding pumps. The process \(X(t)=(X_1(t),...,X_6(t))\) is a vector-valued continuous time Markov chain. Let \(S(t)=X_1(t)+\cdots+X_6(t)\) denote the total number of customers in the system at time \(t\), including any customers in service.

Write a program to simulate the customer arrivals and services and the values of \(X_i(t)\) over a long time period, say a week. You will use your simulation results to approximate the following items, so consider all parts below when designing your code.

  • The long run distribution of the number of cars in the system (waiting or in service).
  • The long run fraction of time there are no cars in the system.
  • The long run average number of customers in the system.
  • Any other features of the long run distribution of the number of cars in the system youâre interested in
  • The long run distribution of the amount of time a customer spends in the system (waiting time + service time). (This will require more work than just finding the number of customers in the system. You will need to track individual customers from the time they enter until the time they leave.)
  • The average time a customer spends in the system.
  • Any other features of the long run distribution of the amount of time a customer spends in the system youâre interested in

Setup

library(tidyverse)
set.seed(545)

Level 1

Letâs begin with a simple system with one pump, one line and one type of customer. We will slowly modify this simulation to fulfill all the requirements of the Costco Gasoline queue.

# Set arrival rate
lambda <- 1
# Set departure rate
mu <- 0.2
# Set time frame - 1 week in minutes
duration <- 60 * 24 * 7
# Initialize time tracker
t <- 0
# Xi = # of customers in system
# This is the underlying DTMC
Xi <- numeric()
# W = waiting times of customers
W <- numeric()
# times = time between states in DTMC
times <- numeric()
# initialize waiting times of people in queue
q_times <- numeric()
# Initialize start state - 0 customers
Xi[[1]] <- 0
# initialize event counter
i <- 1

# Begin simulation
while (t <= duration) {
  # Increment the underlying DTMC Xi to the next step
  # A new event as happened!
  i <- i + 1
  # Get number of people in line just prior to event happening
  ncurr <- Xi[[i-1]]
  
  # If there were no people in line before the event...
  if (ncurr == 0) {
    # Get time to event since last event using lambda only 
    #   since event must be car arriving, not leaving
    wait <- rexp(1, lambda)
    # Add wait time until next state to times vector
    times <- c(times, wait)
    # Add wait time to overall time
    t <- t + wait
    # There is now one person in the queue who is being serviced!
    q_times <- 0
    Xi[[i]] <- 1
  # Otherwise, if there are >0 people in queue prior to event happening...
  } else {
    # Get wait time. It can either be person leaving or 
    wait <- rexp(1, mu + lambda)
    # Add wait time until next state to times vector
    times <- c(times, wait)
    # Add wait time to overall time
    t <- t + wait
    # Add wait time to everyone who is currently in queue
    q_times <- q_times + wait
    # Generate next state of DTMC Xi
    # Either -1 wp mu/(mu+lambda) or 1 wp lambda/(mu+lambda)
    # This is based off the exponential race property
    increment <- sample(c(-1, 1), 1, prob = c(mu, lambda))
    Xi[[i]] <- ncurr + increment
    # If someone is leaving...
    if (increment == -1) {
      # That means we now have a complete wait time
      # Pop the first time off the queue and add it to the list of waiting times
      #   W
      W <- c(W, q_times[[1]])
      if (length(q_times) == 1) {
        q_times <- numeric()
      } else {
        q_times <- q_times[2:length(q_times)]
      }
    # If a car is arriving...
    } else if (increment == 1) {
      # Add a new person's waiting time to the queue
      q_times <- c(q_times, 0)
    }
  }
}
times <- c(times, 0)

Letâs view the CTMC:

Level 2

Now on to the next level. Letâs simulate two pumps on the same side. What changes here? The leaving rate, instead of simply being mu, is now \(\min(X_i(t), 2)\cdot\mu\) Either there is 1 person in the queue, which means that they leave at a rate \(\mu\), or there are 2 or more people in the queue, in which case they leave at a rate \(2\mu\). Modifying the simulation:

lambda <- 1; mu <- 0.2
duration <- 60 * 24 * 7
t <- 0
Xi <- numeric(); W <- numeric()
times <- numeric()
q_times <- numeric()
Xi[[1]] <- 0
i <- 1

while (t <= duration) {
  i <- i + 1
  ncurr <- Xi[[i-1]]
  
  # New leaving rate, equal to 0 if there are no cars
  lrate <- min(ncurr, 2)*mu
  wait <- rexp(1, lrate + lambda)
  times <- c(times, wait)
  t <- t + wait
  q_times <- q_times + wait
  # New increment proportions in exponential race
  increment <- sample(c(-1, 1), 1, prob = c(lrate, lambda))
  Xi[[i]] <- ncurr + increment
  
  if (increment == -1) {
    if (ncurr == 1) {
      W <- c(W, q_times[[1]])
      q_times <- numeric()
    } else {
      # We need to choose who leaves if there are 2 people at pumps
      # It's a 50/50 chance by the exponential race
      # We also need to maintain ordering
      leaves <- sample(c(1, 2), 1)
      if (leaves == 1) {
        W <- c(W, q_times[[1]])
        if (ncurr == 2) {
          q_times <- q_times[[2]]
        } else if (ncurr == 3) {
          q_times <- q_times[c(3,2)]
        } else {
          q_times <- c(q_times[c(3,2)], q_times[4:length(q_times)])
        }
      } else if (leaves == 2) {
        W <- c(W, q_times[[2]])
        if (ncurr == 2) {
          q_times <- q_times[[1]]
        } else if (ncurr == 3) {
          q_times <- q_times[c(1,3)]
        } else {
          q_times <- c(q_times[c(1,3)], q_times[4:length(q_times)])
        }
      }
    }
  } else if (increment == 1) {
    q_times <- c(q_times, 0)
  }
}
times <- c(times, 0)
plot(cumsum(times), Xi, type="s", main="Simulated Queue Length CTMC")

Level 3

Now, letâs simulate two pumps on either side. We will now have two queues. The leaving rate is now \(\min(X_1(t),2)+\min(X_2(t),2)\). Modifying the simulation:

lambda <- 1; mu <- 0.2
duration <- 60 * 24 * 7
t <- 0
# S is the total in queue across all Xi queues
# X is a matrix where each column is a different queue
# Beacuse there are 2 queues, X now has 2 columns instead of "1" column like 
#   before
S <- numeric(); X <- t(matrix(c(0, 0))); W <- numeric()
times <- numeric()
# Times of people in queue are now also 2-column
q_times <- list(numeric(), numeric())
S[[1]] <- 0
i <- 1

while (t <= duration) {
  i <- i + 1
  ncurr <- X[i-1,]
  # Set new states equal to old states, we will update the state of the queue
  #   that changes
  X <- rbind(X, ncurr)
  # New leaving rate. It will be equal to 0 if no one is at the queues
  lrate <- sum(sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, 2))) * mu
  
  # New wait time
  wait <- rexp(1, rate = lrate + lambda)
  times <- c(times, wait)
  t <- t + wait
  q_times <- lapply(q_times, function(x) x + wait)
  increment <- sample(c(-1, 1), 1, prob = c(lrate, lambda))
  
  if (increment == 1) {
    # If person arrives, they arrive at the shortest queue
    queue <- which(ncurr == min(ncurr))
    # If more than one shortest queue, choose a random one
    if (length(queue) > 1) {
      queue <- sample(queue, 1)
    }
    # Update state of the selected queue. All other states stay the same.
    X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] + 1
    
    q_times[[queue]] <- c(q_times[[queue]], 0)
  } else if (increment == -1) {
    # Choose which queue to leave
    # Probability of a queue being the one left is proportional to the number
    #   of cars at its pump
    queue <- sample(c(1,2), 1, prob = sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, 2)))
    # Update state of the selected queue. All other states stay the same.
    X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] - 1
    
    q_times_i <- q_times[[queue]]
    if (ncurr[queue] == 1) {
      W <- c(W, q_times_i[[1]])
      q_times[[queue]] <- numeric()
    } else {
      leaves <- sample(c(1, 2), 1)
      if (leaves == 1) {
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[1]])
        if (ncurr[queue] == 2) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[[2]]
        } else if (ncurr[queue] == 3) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[c(3,2)]
        } else {
          q_times_i <- c(q_times_i[c(3,2)], q_times_i[4:length(q_times_i)])
        }
      } else if (leaves == 2) {
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[2]])
        if (ncurr[queue] == 2) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[[1]]
        } else if (ncurr[queue] == 3) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[c(1,3)]
        } else {
          q_times_i <- c(q_times_i[c(1,3)], q_times_i[4:length(q_times_i)])
        }
      }
      q_times[[queue]] <- q_times_i
    }
  }
  S[[i]] <- sum(X[i,])
}
times <- c(times, 0)
rownames(X) <- NULL
plot(cumsum(times), S, type="s", main="Simulated Queue Length CTMC")

hist(X[,1])

hist(X[,2])

hist(S)

hist(W)

Level 4

We know that cars have left/right/either preference, so letâs incorporate that here. Modifying the simulation:

lambda <- 1; mu <- 0.2
duration <- 60 * 24 * 7
t <- 0
S <- numeric(); X <- t(matrix(c(0, 0))); W <- numeric()
times <- numeric()
q_times <- list(numeric(), numeric())
S[[1]] <- 0
i <- 1

while (t <= duration) {
  i <- i + 1
  ncurr <- X[i-1,]
  X <- rbind(X, ncurr)
  lrate <- sum(sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, 2))) * mu
  
  wait <- rexp(1, rate = lrate + lambda)
  times <- c(times, wait)
  t <- t + wait
  q_times <- lapply(q_times, function(x) x + wait)
  increment <- sample(c(-1, 1), 1, prob = c(lrate, lambda))
  
  if (increment == 1) {
    # Generate car preference based on distribution
    pref <- sample(c("Odd", "Even", "Both"), 1, prob = c(0.3, 0.3, 0.4))
    # If car preference is odd/left side pump...
    if (pref == "Odd") {
      # Get the minimum of the odd indices
      pref_min <- min(ncurr[seq(1, length(ncurr), by = 2)])
      # Find the queue with the odd argmin
      queue <- which((ncurr == pref_min) & ((1:length(ncurr) + 1) %% 2 == 0))
    # If car preference is even/right side pump...
    } else if (pref == "Even") {
      # Get the minimum of the even indices
      pref_min <- min(ncurr[seq(2, length(ncurr), by = 2)])
      # Find the queue with the even argmin
      queue <- which((ncurr == pref_min) & ((1:length(ncurr)) %% 2 == 0))
    # If no car preference...
    } else if (pref == "Both") {
      # Find queue with overall argmin
      queue <- which(ncurr == min(ncurr))
    }
    # If more than 1 min, randomly choose 1
    if (length(queue) > 1) {
      queue <- sample(queue, 1)
    }
    X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] + 1
    
    q_times[[queue]] <- c(q_times[[queue]], 0)
  } else if (increment == -1) {
    queue <- sample(c(1,2), 1, prob = sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, 2)))
    X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] - 1
    
    q_times_i <- q_times[[queue]]
    if (ncurr[queue] == 1) {
      W <- c(W, q_times_i[[1]])
      q_times[[queue]] <- numeric()
    } else {
      leaves <- sample(c(1, 2), 1)
      if (leaves == 1) {
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[1]])
        if (ncurr[queue] == 2) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[[2]]
        } else if (ncurr[queue] == 3) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[c(3,2)]
        } else {
          q_times_i <- c(q_times_i[c(3,2)], q_times_i[4:length(q_times_i)])
        }
      } else if (leaves == 2) {
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[2]])
        if (ncurr[queue] == 2) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[[1]]
        } else if (ncurr[queue] == 3) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[c(1,3)]
        } else {
          q_times_i <- c(q_times_i[c(1,3)], q_times_i[4:length(q_times_i)])
        }
      }
      q_times[[queue]] <- q_times_i
    }
  }
  S[[i]] <- sum(X[i,])
}
times <- c(times, 0)
rownames(X) <- NULL
plot(cumsum(times), S, type="s", main="Simulated Queue Length CTMC")

Final Simulation

Now, letâs increase the number of queues to 6 (or 3 islands). This will complete our simulation by satisfying all specified requirements. Modifying the simulation:

lambda <- 1; mu <- 0.2
duration <- 60 * 24 * 7; t <- 0
# There are now 6 queues
q <- 6
S <- numeric(); X <- t(matrix(rep(0, q))); W <- numeric()
times <- numeric()
q_times <- rep(list(numeric()), times=q)
S[[1]] <- 0; i <- 1

while (t <= duration) {
  i <- i + 1
  ncurr <- X[i-1,]
  X <- rbind(X, ncurr)
  lrate <- sum(sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, 2))) * mu
  wait <- rexp(1, rate = lrate + lambda)
  times <- c(times, wait)
  t <- t + wait
  q_times <- lapply(q_times, function(x) x + wait)
  increment <- sample(c(-1, 1), 1, prob = c(lrate, lambda))
  
  if (increment == 1) {
    pref <- sample(c("Odd", "Even", "Both"), 1, prob = c(0.3, 0.3, 0.4))
    if (pref == "Odd") {
      pref_min <- min(ncurr[seq(1, length(ncurr), by = 2)])
      queue <- which((ncurr == pref_min) & ((1:length(ncurr) + 1) %% 2 == 0))
    } else if (pref == "Even") {
      pref_min <- min(ncurr[seq(2, length(ncurr), by = 2)])
      queue <- which((ncurr == pref_min) & ((1:length(ncurr)) %% 2 == 0))
    } else if (pref == "Both") {
      queue <- which(ncurr == min(ncurr))
    }

    }

  } else if (increment == -1) {
    queue <- sample(1:q, 1, prob = sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, 2)))
    X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] - 1
    
    q_times_i <- q_times[[queue]]
    if (ncurr[queue] == 1) {
      W <- c(W, q_times_i[[1]])

          q_times_i <- q_times_i[c(3,2)]
        } else {
          q_times_i <- c(q_times_i[c(3,2)], q_times_i[4:length(q_times_i)])
        }
      } else if (leaves == 2) {
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[2]])
        if (ncurr[queue] == 2) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[[1]]
        } else if (ncurr[queue] == 3) {
          q_times_i <- q_times_i[c(1,3)]
        } else {
          q_times_i <- c(q_times_i[c(1,3)], q_times_i[4:length(q_times_i)])
        }
      }
      q_times[[queue]] <- q_times_i
    }
  }
  S[[i]] <- sum(X[i,])

props <- time_dist %>%

props
S_mean <- props %>%
  mutate(weight = S * time) %>%
  pull(weight) %>%
  sum()

Part 2

Change some features of the set up and investigate how your changes effect the average number of customers in the system, and the average time a customer spends in the system.

Letâs investigate how changing the âdimensionsâ of the gas pump layout affects the waiting time and number of customers in the system. In this particular example, since we have 12 pumps, how would the mean waiting time and mean number of customers in the system compare for the following layouts:

  • 1 queue, 12 pumps per queue
  • 2 queues, 6 pumps per queue
  • 3 queues, 4 pumps per queue
  • 4 queues, 3 pumps per queue
  • 6 queues, 2 pumps per queue
  • 12 queues, 1 pump per queue

All rules outlined in the problem will apply.

First, letâs generalize our simulation as a function that takes in parameters for the number of queues and the number of pumps at each queue:

costco_sim <- function(q, npumps, sidepref = TRUE) {
  lambda <- 1; mu <- 0.2
  duration <- 60 * 24 * 7; t <- 0
  S <- numeric(); X <- t(matrix(rep(0, q))); W <- numeric()
  times <- numeric()
  q_times <- rep(list(numeric()), times=q)
  S[[1]] <- 0; i <- 1
  
  while (t <= duration) {
    i <- i + 1
    ncurr <- X[i-1,]
    X <- rbind(X, ncurr)
    lrate <- sum(sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, npumps))) * mu
    wait <- rexp(1, rate = lrate + lambda)
    times <- c(times, wait)
    t <- t + wait
    q_times <- lapply(q_times, function(x) x + wait)
    increment <- sample(c(-1, 1), 1, prob = c(lrate, lambda))
    
    if (increment == 1) {
      # Edit vehicle preference to handle one queue
      if ((q == 1) | !(sidepref)) {
        queue <- which(ncurr == min(ncurr))
      } else {
        pref <- sample(c("Odd", "Even", "Both"), 1, prob = c(0.3, 0.3, 0.4))
        if (pref == "Odd") {
          pref_min <- min(ncurr[seq(1, length(ncurr), by = 2)])
          queue <- which((ncurr == pref_min) & ((1:length(ncurr) + 1) %% 2 == 0))
        } else if (pref == "Even") {
          pref_min <- min(ncurr[seq(2, length(ncurr), by = 2)])
          queue <- which((ncurr == pref_min) & ((1:length(ncurr)) %% 2 == 0))
        } else if (pref == "Both") {
          queue <- which(ncurr == min(ncurr))
        }
      }
      
      if (length(queue) > 1) {
        queue <- sample(queue, 1)
      }
      X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] + 1
      
      q_times[[queue]] <- c(q_times[[queue]], 0)
    } else if (increment == -1) {
      queue <- sample(1:q, 1, prob = sapply(ncurr, function(x) min(x, npumps)))
      X[[i,queue]] <- ncurr[queue] - 1
      
      q_times_i <- q_times[[queue]]
      if (ncurr[queue] == 1) {
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[1]])
        q_times[[queue]] <- numeric()
      # Modify for general cases for different pump numbers
      } else if (ncurr[queue] <= npumps) {
        leaves <- sample(1:ncurr[queue], 1)
        stays <- c(1:ncurr[queue])[1:ncurr[queue] != leaves]
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[leaves]])
        q_times[[queue]] = q_times[[queue]][stays]
      } else {
        leaves <- sample(1:npumps, 1)
        stays <- c(1:npumps)[1:npumps != leaves]
        W <- c(W, q_times_i[[leaves]])
        q_times[[queue]] <- c(q_times[[queue]][stays], 
                              q_times[[queue]][(npumps+1):ncurr[queue]])
      }
    }
    S[[i]] <- sum(X[i,])
  }
  times <- c(times, 0)
  rownames(X) <- NULL
  
  S_mean <- cbind(S, times) %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    group_by(S) %>%
    summarize(time = sum(times)) %>%
    mutate(time = time / sum(time)) %>%
    mutate(weight = S * time) %>%
    pull(weight) %>%
    sum()
  
  return(c(S_mean, mean(W)))
}

With Vehicle Side Preference

Now, letâs run on all queue/pump dimensions that result in a total of 12 pumps:

dims <- list(c(1,12), c(2, 6), c(3, 4), c(4, 3), c(6, 2), c(12, 1))
results_all <- numeric()
for (dim in dims) {
  q <- dim[1]; npumps <- dim[2]
  results <- costco_sim(q, npumps, sidepref = TRUE)
  results_all <- rbind(results_all, results)
}
rownames(results_all) <- NULL
colnames(results_all) <- c("S_mean", "W_mean")
results_table <- cbind(
  "nqueue" = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12),
  "npumps" = c(12, 6, 4, 3, 2, 1),
  results_all
) %>%
  as.data.frame()
results_table
plot(results_all[,"S_mean"], xaxt = "n", type="l",
     xlab="layout (nqueues, npumps)", ylab="ncustomers", 
     main="Mean count of customers in system by layout")
axis(side = 1, at = seq(1, 6, by = 1), 
     labels = c("1,12", "2,6", "3,4", "4,3", "6,2", "12,1"))

plot(results_all[,"W_mean"], xaxt = "n", type="l",
     xlab="layout (nqueues, npumps)", ylab="minutes", 
     main="Mean customer waiting time by layout")
axis(side = 1, at = seq(1, 6, by = 1), 
     labels = c("1,12", "2,6", "3,4", "4,3", "6,2", "12,1"))

We can see that based on the results of our simulation, the average number of customers in the system is minimized when there is 4 queue of 3 pumps each, and the average waiting time of each customer is minimized when there are 2 queues of 6 pumps each. In general, layouts with even numbers of queues performed the best.

Without Vehicle Side Preference

What happens if we remove vehicle side preference â that is, what if we alter the simulation so no vehicles prefer the right or left side? # heyyyyy letâs see if you notice this

dims <- list(c(1,12), c(2, 6), c(3, 4), c(4, 3), c(6, 2), c(12, 1))
results_all <- numeric()
for (dim in dims) {
  q <- dim[1]; npumps <- dim[2]
  results <- costco_sim(q, npumps, sidepref = FALSE)
  results_all <- rbind(results_all, results)
}
rownames(results_all) <- NULL
colnames(results_all) <- c("S_mean", "W_mean")
results_table <- cbind(
  "nqueue" = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12),
  "npumps" = c(12, 6, 4, 3, 2, 1),
  results_all
) %>%
  as.data.frame()
results_table
plot(results_all[,"S_mean"], xaxt = "n", type="l",
     xlab="layout (nqueues, npumps)", ylab="ncustomers", 
     main="Mean count of customers in system by layout")
axis(side = 1, at = seq(1, 6, by = 1), 
     labels = c("1,12", "2,6", "3,4", "4,3", "6,2", "12,1"))

plot(results_all[,"W_mean"], xaxt = "n", type="l",
     xlab="layout (nqueues, npumps)", ylab="minutes", 
     main="Mean customer waiting time by layout")
axis(side = 1, at = seq(1, 6, by = 1), 
     labels = c("1,12", "2,6", "3,4", "4,3", "6,2", "12,1"))

We can see that based on the results of our simulation, the average number of customers in the system is minimized when there is 12 queue of 1 pumps each, and the average waiting time of each customer is minimized when there are 12 queues of 1 pumps each. Performance appears to be less dependent on odd/even numbers of queues.

In general, for both cases with and without vehicle pump side preference, the effect size of changing the layout is relatively small, with the mean number of customers in the system staying at around 5 and the mean waiting time of a customer remaining at around 5 minutes.
